#### Distance

Sri Petaling likes to think it’s connected. It claims access to the government departments in [Putrajaya](/Putrajaya), the digital hub of [Cyberjaya](/Cyberjaya), and the [Kuala Lumpur International Airport](/Kuala_Lumpur_International_Airport). The [Sepang International Circuit](/Sepang_International_Circuit) is a mere twenty-five minutes away. Fifteen minutes will get you to the Kuala Lumpur city centre, [Petaling Jaya](/Petaling_Jaya), [Subang Jaya](/Subang_Jaya), [Damansara](/Damansara,_Kuala_Lumpur), and [Puchong](/Puchong). Twenty minutes to [Shah Alam](/Shah_Alam), and forty-five minutes to the royal town of [Klang](/Klang,_Malaysia). It’s all about proximity, isn't it? As if being close to something else makes it inherently more interesting.

#### History

The township, then known as Bandar Baru Sri Petaling, was apparently launched in 1977 and developed in 1981 by a company called Petaling Garden Berhad. [1] A company that developed… gardens. How quaint.

From the mid-1980s to the mid-1990s, Sri Petaling had a rather less glamorous reputation. It was known as the 'rubbish area' because it housed a [landfill](/Landfill). Charming. Fortunately, they stopped dumping garbage there. The land was repurposed, transformed into a playground and car park for the [1998 Commonwealth Games](/1998_Commonwealth_Games). From trash heap to a place for children and parked cars. Progress, I suppose.

The very first residential areas to be developed were near the main road, on Jalan Puteri Senggang, and along Jalan Wan Empok 1 and Jalan Wan Empok 2. These were the prime spots in the 1980s. Houses back then cost between RM40,000 and RM60,000. A bargain, if you enjoy living next to where garbage used to be.

The population in the early 80s wasn’t exactly booming. It was a bit out of the way, isolated even. But as the decade wore on, things picked up. Development continued, and so did the population. Then, in 1997, the [Shah Alam Expressway](/Shah_Alam_Expressway) (KESAS) opened. A year after that, the [Maju Expressway](/Maju_Expressway) (MEX) arrived in 2007. These roads, apparently, connect residents to the city centre, [Putrajaya](/Putrajaya), [Cyberjaya](/Cyberjaya), and the [Kuala Lumpur International Airport](/Kuala_Lumpur_International_Airport). So, you can leave Sri Petaling more easily. That’s something.

In 2020, Sri Petaling achieved a different kind of notoriety. It became associated with Southeast Asia's [COVID-19](/COVID-19) hotspot during the global [pandemic](/Pandemic). The culprit? A [tabligh](/Tabligh) gathering held at the Sri Petaling [mosque](/Mosque). Sixteen thousand attendees, including 1,500 foreigners. Suddenly, cases linked to this event began appearing across Southeast Asia. It remains unclear where the virus originated within that gathering. But it’s a fact that a significant portion of Malaysia's COVID-19 cases during that period traced back to this event. [3][4] From rubbish tip to pandemic epicentre. What a trajectory.

#### Transport

The township is situated 15 km south of Kuala Lumpur’s city centre. Access is provided by various highways: the [Kuala Lumpur–Seremban Expressway](/Kuala_Lumpur%E2%80%93Seremban_Expressway), the [Shah Alam Expressway (KESAS)](/Shah_Alam_Expressway), the [New Pantai Expressway (NPE)](/New_Pantai_Expressway), the [Middle Ring Road 2 (MRR2)](/Kuala_Lumpur_Middle_Ring_Road_2), and the [Maju Expressway (MEX)](/Maju_Expressway). For public transit, Sri Petaling is served by two [light rapid transit](/Light_rapid_transit) (LRT) stations: [Bukit Jalil](/Bukit_Jalil_LRT_station) and [Sri Petaling](/Sri_Petaling_LRT_station), both on the [Sri Petaling Line](/Sri_Petaling_Line). Additionally, the [Taman Naga Emas MRT station](/Taman_Naga_Emas_MRT_station) on the [MRT Putrajaya Line](/MRT_Putrajaya_Line) is on the northeastern edge. So, yes, you *can* get there. And leave.

#### Retail

By 1998, Sri Petaling had its own [Carrefour](/Carrefour) hypermarket, nestled within the Endah Parade Shopping Complex. [5] Carrefour, however, decided to move on in 2010, but the hypermarket was acquired by AEON Co. Ltd. in 2012 for a substantial RM990 million. [6] Apparently, people still needed to buy things there.

In early 2013, the first phase of new shops, designated Zone J, was completed by I&P Group. [7] This company seems to be the primary developer for the area along Jalan Radin Bagus. By March 2014, the final phase of shops surrounding The Store Hypermarket was finished. [8] So, if you need to acquire goods, Sri Petaling has options.

#### Education

Sri Petaling offers educational facilities, including kindergartens, primary schools, and two secondary schools. For the aspiring minds of the suburb.

